id: pm-pl53
title: Extension sandbox profiles are advisory-only — no runtime enforcement of declared permission boundaries
description: "extension-policy.ts evaluates sandbox profiles (none/restricted/strict) and produces warnings/blocks based on the manifest `permissions` declaration and `sandbox_profile`. However, the actual extension module is loaded via dynamic import() in the same Node.js process with no VM isolation, permissions API restrictions, or OS-level sandbox. The 'restricted' and 'strict' profiles only block the extension from LOADING if it declares conflicting permissions — they do not prevent a malicious extension from actually spawning processes, writing files, or opening network connections at runtime. An ADR already records this as advisory design. The gap worth tracking: a clear user-facing warning in `pm extension doctor` and `pm health` that sandbox profiles are declaration-based, not runtime-enforced, so users understand the trust model."
type: Feature
status: closed
priority: 3
tags[3]: "area:extensions",docs,security
